+.. SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0
+
+====================================
+Hyperion Kernel Performance Tuning
+====================================
+
+:Author: Hyperion Kernel Project
+:Version: 2.2.2
+:Date: 2026
+
+This guide documents the tuning decisions made in the Hyperion v2.2.2
+kernel configuration. Each section explains what a feature does, why it
+is enabled, and what the expected impact is on a modern x86_64 desktop or
+workstation running Linux in 2026.
+
+.. contents::
+   :local:
+   :depth: 2
+
+BPF & JIT Compilation
+======================
+
+The Berkeley Packet Filter (BPF) subsystem is the foundation of modern
+Linux networking, security policy enforcement, and CPU scheduling in 2026.
+BPF programs must execute at native machine speed via the JIT compiler.
+
+**CONFIG_BPF_JIT=y**
+  Compiles BPF bytecode to native x86_64 instructions at program load time.
+  Without JIT, BPF programs run in a software interpreter that is 10-100x
+  slower. Every XDP hook, every Cilium network policy rule, every sched-ext
+  scheduling decision requires JIT to be viable.
+
+**CONFIG_BPF_JIT_ALWAYS_ON=y**
+  Removes the BPF interpreter entirely. This eliminates a class of
+  speculative execution vulnerabilities (Spectre-BPF) that require an
+  interpreter to be exploitable. It also prevents accidental fallback to
+  slow interpreted execution if JIT fails on an unusual program.
+
+**CONFIG_BPF_JIT_DEFAULT_ON=y**
+  Makes JIT active immediately on boot without requiring the administrator
+  to set ``net.core.bpf_jit_enable=1`` via sysctl. Required for sched-ext
+  and Cilium to work correctly out of the box.
+
+**CONFIG_BPF_UNPRIV_DEFAULT_OFF=y**
+  Prevents unprivileged users from loading BPF programs. The unprivileged
+  BPF interface has been the prerequisite or entry point for numerous
+  privilege escalation vulnerabilities (CVE-2021-3490, CVE-2022-0185,
+  CVE-2023-2163). Requiring ``CAP_BPF`` or ``CAP_SYS_ADMIN`` closes this
+  attack surface with no impact on legitimate system BPF usage.
+
+sched-ext: Runtime BPF Schedulers
+===================================
+
+Linux 6.12 introduced the extensible scheduler class (sched-ext), which
+allows the CPU scheduling policy to be replaced at runtime with a BPF
+program — without rebooting or recompiling the kernel.
+
+**CONFIG_SCHED_CLASS_EXT=y**
+  Enables the sched-ext framework. With this option the following
+  schedulers can be loaded at runtime via ``scx_loader`` or directly::
+
+    # Interactive-first desktop scheduler (recommended for gaming)
+    scx_bpfland
+
+    # Latency-critical virtual deadline (CachyOS default)
+    scx_lavd
+
+    # NUMA-aware multi-layer scheduler (Meta, good for workstations)
+    scx_rusty
+
+  Switch between schedulers without a reboot::
+
+    # Load a scheduler
+    sudo scx_bpfland &
+
+    # Unload (reverts to CFS)
+    sudo pkill scx_bpfland
+
+  See: https://github.com/sched-ext/scx
+
+x86 Architecture Tuning
+========================
+
+**CONFIG_X86_X2APIC=y**
+  Enables the x2APIC interface which scales interrupt routing to 2^32
+  logical CPUs. On EPYC and Threadripper platforms with >255 logical CPUs
+  this is required. On desktop platforms it reduces APIC register access
+  overhead by replacing MMIO accesses with MSR writes.
+
+**CONFIG_X86_CHECK_BIOS_CORRUPTION=y**
+  Scans the BIOS-reserved memory region for corruption at boot and on a
+  periodic timer. Some firmware implementations incorrectly write into
+  kernel memory regions during ACPI events. This option detects and logs
+  such corruption before it causes data loss or silent memory errors.
+
+**CONFIG_X86_INTEL_USERCOPY_CHECK=y**
+  Selects the enhanced REP MOVSB/STOSB (ERMSB) path for ``copy_to_user``
+  and ``copy_from_user`` on Intel Haswell and newer processors. ERMSB
+  provides approximately 2x the throughput of the generic copy path for
+  medium-to-large transfers, which benefits system calls that move large
+  buffers (read/write on NVMe, sendfile, splice).
+
+**CONFIG_X86_AMD_PSTATE_DEFAULT_MODE=3**
+  Sets AMD P-State to Active EPP mode on boot. In mode 3 the CPU hardware
+  manages its own frequency transitions within the Energy Performance
+  Preference (EPP) hint set by the OS. The hardware reacts to load changes
+  in microseconds — far faster than any software cpufreq governor — which
+  gives better single-core boost behaviour during bursty workloads like
+  game frame rendering.
+
+Filesystem & Integrity
+======================
+
+**CONFIG_FS_ENCRYPTION=y**
+  Per-file encryption infrastructure (fscrypt). Enables ``tune2fs -O
+  encrypt`` on ext4, encryption on f2fs, and provides the key management
+  infrastructure used by Android, ChromeOS, and enterprise ext4 setups.
+
+**CONFIG_FS_VERITY=y and CONFIG_FS_VERITY_BUILTIN_SIGNATURES=y**
+  Per-file Merkle-tree integrity verification. The verity hash tree is
+  computed over the file's data blocks at setup time and verified
+  on-demand at page read time. Used by Android APK signing, Chromium
+  component verification, and Flatpak runtime integrity. Builtin
+  signatures allow verity digests to be verified against the kernel
+  keyring, which IPE (below) uses for policy enforcement.
+
+**CONFIG_UNICODE=y and CONFIG_UNICODE_UTF8_DATA=y**
+  NFC UTF-8 case-folding table for case-insensitive directory lookups.
+  Required by ``mkfs.ext4 -O casefold`` and f2fs ``-o extent_cache``.
+  Steam on Linux requires case-insensitive paths for Windows game
+  asset compatibility. Wine/Proton uses the same mechanism.
+
+Integrity Policy Enforcement (IPE)
+====================================
+
+IPE is the Linux in-tree integrity policy framework introduced in Linux
+6.9. It enforces policies that restrict code execution based on the
+integrity of the filesystem the code resides on — as measured by
+dm-verity or fs-verity at boot or mount time.
+
+**CONFIG_SECURITY_IPE=y**
+  Enables the IPE LSM. IPE policies are expressed as simple plaintext
+  rules and loaded via securityfs. Example policy snippet::
+
+    policy_name="hyperion-lockdown" policy_version=0.0.1
+    DEFAULT action=DENY
+    op=EXECUTE boot_verified=TRUE action=ALLOW
+    op=EXECUTE dmverity_roothash=sha256:abc123... action=ALLOW
+
+**CONFIG_IPE_PROP_BOOT_VERIFIED=y**
+  Exposes a ``boot_verified`` property in IPE policy that is true for
+  any file residing on a dm-verity volume whose root hash was measured
+  by the bootloader. Combined with a UEFI Secure Boot chain this allows
+  enforcing "only execute code from the verified root filesystem."
+
+ZRAM Multi-Stream Compression
+==============================
+
+**CONFIG_ZRAM_MULTI_COMP=y**
+  Enables two compression streams per zram device. The primary stream
+  uses a high-ratio algorithm (ZSTD) for freshly written pages. The
+  secondary stream uses a fast algorithm (LZ4) for pages being written
+  back to the backing device under memory pressure. This gives the best
+  of both worlds: strong compression when RAM is available, fast
+  decompression throughput when the system is under pressure.
+
+  Example zram setup with multi-stream::
+
+    # Create a 16 GB zram device
+    echo 16G > /sys/block/zram0/disksize
+
+    # Set primary algorithm (ZSTD for ratio)
+    echo zstd > /sys/block/zram0/comp_algorithm
+
+    # Enable secondary algorithm (LZ4 for speed under pressure)
+    echo lz4 > /sys/block/zram0/comp_algorithm2
+
+    mkswap /dev/zram0
+    swapon -p 100 /dev/zram0
+
+Debugging Discipline
+=====================
+
+The following options are intentionally disabled in production builds.
+Each one is documented here so the decision is visible and reviewable:
+
+- ``CONFIG_DEBUG_PREEMPT`` — adds ~3% overhead to every preemption path.
+  Unnecessary when the scheduler itself is correct.
+
+- ``CONFIG_PROVE_LOCKING`` (lockdep) — adds ~40% overhead to all lock
+  operations. Use a debug kernel for lockdep analysis.
+
+- ``CONFIG_DEBUG_ATOMIC_SLEEP`` — fires false positives in audio RT
+  threads that legitimately sleep with spinlocks held under PREEMPT_RT.
+
+- ``CONFIG_DEBUG_VM`` — per-page overhead on every page map/unmap.
+  Unacceptable for a gaming or media workload.
+
+**CONFIG_STACKTRACE=y** is kept enabled. It has zero overhead when no
+probe is active and is required by ``perf``, ``bpftrace``, BPF
+``BPF_STACK_ID`` maps, and kernel crash dump symbolication.
+
